'''Every Single Word (Spoken by a Person of Color)''' is a [[Tumblr]] blog and [[YouTube]] channel that features videos on all the lines spoken by [[people of color]] (POC) in both [[Contemporary history|contemporary]] and classic films. Created by Dylan Marron, the videos are an attempt to highlight the lack of casting and involvement of POC in [[Hollywood]] produced films, in addition to highlighting his own experiences in attempting to be cast in films as a [[Venezuelan American]].<ref name="Post">{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Soraya Nadia |date=July 10, 2015 |title=Meet Dylan Marron, the actor and playwright behind those ‘every single word spoken by a person of color’ YouTube videos |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/style-blog/wp/2015/07/10/meet-dylan-marron-the-actor-and-playwright-behind-those-every-single-word-spoken-by-a-person-of-color-youtube-videos/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Harris |first=Aisha |date=June 24, 2015 |title=A Brilliant Video Series Shows Just How Few Words Are Spoken by People of Color in Movies |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/06/24/_every_single_word_spoken_by_a_person_of_color_in____video_series_calls.html |newspaper=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref>
The reasons for such low amounts of casting of POC in films is stated by Marron to be about fear, because the "people who finance the movies are not going to want to throw millions behind a movie of a non-famous person of color". In addition, default casting for films, even for works or scripts with no specified races for the characters, is to choose [[White people|white]] actors. The novel ''[[The Fault in Our Stars]]'' by [[John Green (author)|John Green]] is noted by Marron as a work with no races given for the characters and one that has had worldwide success in its book form, but the main cast for the film were chosen by the producing studio to be entirely white.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |last=Gajanan |first=Mahita |date=July 8, 2015 |title=Famous films re-edited to highlight Hollywood's race problem |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/08/person-of-colour-hollywood-films-diversity |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref> Manohla Dargis, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', noted that Marron's videos show that even when POC are cast in films, they are often cast in stereotypical roles that function as [[tokenism]] for the casting quota.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |date=August 5, 2015 |title=Report Finds Wide Diversity Gap Among 2014's Top Grossing Films |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/06/movies/report-finds-wide-diversity-gap-among-2014s-top-grossing-films.html?_r=0 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref> ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' compared Marron's videos with other statistics presented in the "2015 Hollywood Diversity Report", which showed that scriptwriters and directors are also rarely POC, along with lead roles in films.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brodeur |first=Michael Andor |date=June 30, 2015 |title=‘Every Single Word’ captures Hollywood’s lack of diversity |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/2015/06/29/every-single-word-captures-hollywood-lack-diversity/flVVN041nZ5SdTLR3YE6TP/story.html |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref>
Several celebrities have praised and shared the blog with their fans, including [[Aziz Ansari]], [[Junot Diaz]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Coggan |first=Devan |date=July 15, 2015 |title=This video project cuts together every line spoken by people of color in movies |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/15/every-single-word-spoken-by-people-of-color-movies |newspaper=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref> [[Kerry Washington]],<ref name="APP"/> and [[Chirlane McCray]].<ref name="MTV"/> The blog was named by Tumblr as the most viral blog of 2015.<ref>{{cite news |last=Vitto |first=Laura |date=December 7, 2015 |title=The 10 most viral Tumblr blogs of 2015 |url=http://mashable.com/2015/12/08/viral-tumblr-blogs-2015/#Nm.QOWTXHGq7 |newspaper=[[Mashable]] |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref>
==History== Marron began producing the video cuts in June 2015 and the popularity of the blog began to increase soon after beginning the project. The idea for the blog came after Marron started a play titled "Every Single Word" for his theater group, called the ''New York Neo Futurists'', which involved a large number of short play pieces by different members. Marron's act consisted of him saying every line by Anjelah Johnson-Reyes in ''[[Enough Said (film)|Enough Said]]''. In 2014, while re-watching the film, he realized that the writer was unable to view POC as separate from service jobs and caused him to form his act for the group. This act eventually led to his investigation of other films and the creation of his video cut blog.<ref>{{cite news |last=Desta |first=Yohana |date=July 8, 2015 |title=Bold video series shows how rarely people of color actually speak in films |url=http://mashable.com/2015/07/08/every-single-word-video-series/#JYboDGaLHsqQ |newspaper=[[Mashable]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Zakarin |first=Jordan |date=June 29, 2015 |title=Meet the Man Fighting Hollywood's Race Problem, One Supercut at a Time |url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/every-single-word-spoken-by-a-person-of-color-122760221847.html |newspaper=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |access-date=October 10, 2015}}</ref>
The coverage of POC representation in the [[Harry Potter]] series by Marron resulted in some controversy. Some fans were upset that the videos pointed out the low representation, "5 minutes and 40 seconds long – out of 1,207 total minutes of run-time" and the [[Racebending|whitewashing]] of the character [[Lavender Brown]] from the black actresses that had played her in the first five movies to the "blond woman" from the sixth movie on, when the character has a heavier involvement and lines in the plot.<ref>{{cite news |last=Minkel |first=Elizabeth |date=September 22, 2015 |title=“Your fave is problematic”: why are we so bad at talking about diversity in pop culture? |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/culture/film/2015/09/your-fave-problematic-why-are-we-so-bad-talking-about-diversity-pop-culture |newspaper=[[New Statesman]] |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> After doing videos on a number of popular movies and series, Marron decided to do a series of videos on every [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] winner since the first award in 1929, in chronological order so that any differences in POC casting can be seen in relation to historical time period.<ref name="Indie">{{cite news |last=Luers |first=Erik |date=December 29, 2015 |title=Interview: Meet Dylan Marron, the Man Behind The 'Every Single Word Spoken By a Person of Color' Video Series |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/interview-meet-dylan-marron-the-man-behind-those-every-single-word-spoken-by-a-person-of-color-youtube-series-20151229 |newspaper=[[Indiewire]] |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> Marron also created a series of videos looking at all the films directed by [[Nancy Meyers]], six films in total. He found that POC representation across all of the films only made up 0.7% of run-time and that most of the characters were not named and were presented as working service jobs.<ref name="Elle">{{cite news |last=Rodulfo |first=Kristina |date=April 27, 2016 |title=These Videos Chart Every Word a Person of Color Speaks in Major Films |url=http://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/news/a35953/every-single-word-tumblr-hollywood-diversity/ |newspaper=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] |access-date=May 2, 2016}}</ref>
A "Every Single Word: The Oscars" [[House concert|live event]] was conducted by Marron on February 28, 2016 in [[New York City]], where the words spoken by people of color during the [[Oscars]] was live cut during viewing.<ref>{{cite news |last=Biese |first=Alex |date=February 22, 2016 |title=Oscar week: Dylan Marron returns to 'Fan Theory' |url=http://www.app.com/story/entertainment/events/fan-theory/2016/02/19/dylan-marron-returns-fan-theory/80616684/ |newspaper=[[Asbury Park Press]] |access-date=March 9, 2016}}</ref>
