'''TV Acres''' was a [[website]] collecting information about [[fictional character|characters]], [[fictional places|places]], and things that have appeared on [[United States|American]] [[television programs]] broadcast from the 1940s through today.<ref name="E&P">Charles Bowen, [http://www.editorandpublisher.com/PrintArticle/TV-Acres-Covers-the-Cultural-Landscape-Of-Our-Time "TV Acres Covers the Cultural Landscape Of Our Time"], ''[[Editor & Publisher]]'', December 12, 2002.</ref><ref>Jim Bainbridge, "Google alert notifies you about any topic, product you request", [[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|''The Gazette'' (Colorado Springs)]], February 13, 2005.  Copy available [http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-2766891.html here] from [[HighBeam Research]] (subscription required).</ref>  The website and its publishing imprint, TV Acres Books, was established by Jerome Holst, a former librarian who now lives in [[Stockport, Ohio]].<ref>Ken Lahmers, [http://www.auroraadvocate.com/news/article/5191059 "Kaleidoscope: Evening stay in Stockport Mill town relaxing"], ''Aurora Advocate'', May 23, 2012.</ref>  The website was named a "hot site" by ''[[USA Today]]'' in 2003.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/tech/webguide/hotsites/2002-11-08-hotsites.htm "Hot Sites"], ''[[USA Today]]'',  April 4, 2003.</ref>

