{{Refimprove|date=June 2016}}
A '''''taqtūqa''''' (Arabic: '''طـقطـوقـة''' plural: '''''taqātīq''''', '''طـقـاطـيـق''') is a genre of light Arabic vocal music sung in regional or colloquial [[Arabic language|Arabic]]. It was associated with female vocalists around the turn of the 20th century, and became very popular during the first decades of the 20th century, as the [[phonograph|gramophone]] and [[Film|cinema]] grew in popularity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TF-5mvvS13oC&pg=PA52&dq=taqtuqa&sig=GRyZWR22ZVTh4Rgw6-Gt2m2Tncw|title=The Voice of Egypt: Umm Kulthūm, Arabic Song, and Egyptian Society in the Twentieth Century|first=Virginia|last=Danielson|date=1 January 1997|publisher=University of Chicago Press|accessdate=23 June 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>

The famous Egyptian singer [[Umm Kulthum (singer)|Umm Kulthum]] recorded ''taqtuqa''s early in her career; her first was "Illi Habbik Ya Hanah" (Joy to Him Who Loved You), composed in 1925 by [[Zakariyya Ahmad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/470/herit2.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 7, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412004217/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/2000/470/herit2.htm |archivedate=April 12, 2008 }}</ref>

